'''Keeree Kanjanapas''' (Thai: คีรี กาญจนพาสน์; {{zh|t=黃創山|p=Huáng Chuàngshān}}; English: Wong Chong Shan) was born in Bangkok, Thailand in 1950. His family roots are in Chaozhou (Guangdong Province). He is a Thai entrepreneur with extensive business interests in mass transit and real estate in Thailand. He is the founder and CEO of the [[BTS Group Holdings|Bangkok Mass Transit System PCL (BTSC)]] "[[BTS Skytrain]]".<ref name="BusinessWeek - Executive Profile - Keeree Kanjanapas">{{cite news|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/businessweek/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=8892467&ticker=BTS:TB&previousCapId=9858081&previousTitle=WORLDSEC%20LTD|title=BTS GROUP HOLDINGS PCL - EXECUTIVE PROFILE - Keeree Kanjanapas|work=[[Bloomberg Businessweek|BusinessWeek]]|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]]|accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesasia/2013/07/03/keeree-kanjanapas-rides-the-skytrain-to-a-1-2-billion-fortune/#4d46b323125c|title=Keeree Kanjanapas Rides The Skytrain To A $1.2 Billion Fortune|last=Asia|first=Forbes|newspaper=Forbes|access-date=2016-12-01}}</ref>
He is chairman of the listed Tanayong Public Company Limited, a long-established property developer and hospitality operator in Thailand.
== Seiko S. A. == Keeree's father Mongkol Kanjanapas (黃子明) was a businessman born in Bangkok and based in both Thailand and Hong Kong. Mongkol founded [[Stelux Holdings]] (寶光實業) and was the importer of [[Seiko]] watches. Keeree decided to use football to promote the Seiko brand and founded one of the most famous and successful football teams ever in Hong Kong, [[Seiko Sports Association]] (精工), in the 1970s and 1980s. Keeree recruited top local player [[Wu Kwok Hung]] from [[South China AA]] by offering him a HK$40,000 annual salary. With Wu and a host of foreign players, the team won a total of nine [[Hong Kong First Division League]] titles including a record seven consecutive titles.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesasia/2016/11/29/against-all-odds-keeree-kanjanapas-built-bangkoks-mass-transit-systems/#198847e64658|title=Against All Odds, Keeree Kanjanapas Built Bangkok's Mass Transit Systems|newspaper=Forbes Asia|access-date=2016-12-01}}</ref>
In 1986, when his plans for a super league was turned down by the [[Hong Kong Football Association]], coupled with a Stelux business downturn, Keeree dissolved the football team after a full house farewell match for Wu Kwok Hung.{{CN|date=August 2017}}
== Personal life == Keeree is the 13th richest man in Thailand as of 2016, up from 19th in 2012. He is worth US$1.55 billion according to [[Forbes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/keeree-kanjanapas/|title=Keeree Kanjanapas|work=Forbes|accessdate=9 August 2013}}</ref>
